{
    "Description": "<h3>Usage</h3><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">file:lines()\n</pre><ul><li><code><strong>file</strong></code>: A valid file handle returned by <code>io.open()</code> or <code>io.popen()</code> opened in read mode.</li></ul><p>   This method returns an iterator function which yields the next line each time it is called.</p><p><br></p><h3>Notes</h3><ul><li><code>io:lines()</code> returns an iterator that reads lines from the file handle.</li><li>Used in a <code>for</code> loop, it will iterate through each line in the file.</li><li>When the end of file is reached, it returns <code>nil</code> to end the loop.</li><li><strong>Unlike</strong> <code><a href=\"@io.lines\" target=\"_blank\">io.lines()</a></code>, the file handle passed to <code>io:lines()</code> <strong>is not automatically closed</strong> at the end of iteration. You must call <code><a href=\"@io:close\" target=\"_blank\">io:close()</a><span class=\"ql-cursor\">﻿﻿﻿﻿</span></code> manually.</li><li>Useful for streaming large files without loading the entire content into memory.</li></ul><p><br></p><h3>Returns</h3><ul><li>The next line of text from the file, or <em><u>(string)</u></em></li><li><code>nil</code> when the end of the file is reached. <em><u>(nil)</u></em></li></ul><p><br></p><h3>Example</h3><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">local file = io.open(\"Lines.txt\", \"a\")&nbsp; -- \"a\" = append mode\nfile:write(\"Adding more text.\\n\")\nfile:close()\nlocal F = io.open(\"Lines.txt\", \"r\")\nfor Line in F:lines() do\n &nbsp; -- Process Line\nend\nF:close()\n</pre>",
    "Name": "io:lines",
    "Parameters": null,
    "ParameterTable": false,
    "SummaryLine": "Reads the file one line at a time."
}